'''''Black Belt''''' is a [[beat 'em up]] video game developed and published by [[Sega]] for the [[Master System]]. The story follows Riki, a martial artist on a mission to save his girlfriend from his rival. Gameplay consists of a series of [[side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] stages where the player battles waves of minor enemies and the occasional [[Boss (video games)#Miniboss|sub-boss]]. Stages culminate in more challenging [[Boss (video games)|boss]] encounters, each requiring the player to use a specific attack to win.

The game is a modification of the Japanese [[Master System#Mark III|Mark III]] title, {{nihongo foot|'''''Hokuto no Ken'''''|北斗の拳||lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}}, based on the [[manga]] series of the same name, which is known as ''[[Fist of the North Star]]'' outside Japan. The export version of the game was released without this license, forcing alterations to character names and graphics. It is one of the earliest works of [[game programmer|programmer]] [[Yuji Naka]] prior to his involvement in ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (1991 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]''.

First released in Japan in July 1986, ''Black Belt'' was localized for North America, Europe, and Brazil. Japan also saw a [[Wii]] [[Virtual Console]] re-release and a [[PlayStation 2]] remake as part of the ''[[Sega Ages]]'' line. While commonly compared to [[Irem]]'s ''[[Kung-Fu Master (video game)|Kung-Fu Master]]'' in both visuals and mechanics, ''Black Belt'' received mixed reactions from critics with some consensus on its boss fights being a positive highlight and its levels being too repetitive.

==Plot and gameplay==
[[File:Black_Belt_1986_Gameplay.png|thumb|left|The player character Riki battles enemies in the third chapter. The player's health meter, remaining time, and score are displayed at the top.]]
''Black Belt'' is a [[beat 'em up]] in which  the player takes control of a martial artist named Riki{{efn|Named {{nihongo|[[Kenshiro]]|ケンシロウ|Kenshirō}} in the original Japanese version}}, who sets out to rescue his girlfriend Kyoko{{efn|Named {{nihongo|[[List of Fist of the North Star characters#Yuria|Yuria]]|ユリア|Yuria}} in the original Japanese version}} from his rival Wang{{efn|Named {{nihongo|[[Raoh]]|ラオウ|Raō}} in the original Japanese version}}. The game is composed of a series of left-to-right, [[side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] stages (or "chapters") in which Riki must utilize punches, kicks, and jumps to defeat different types of minor underlings and the occasional [[Boss (video games)#Miniboss|sub-boss]].<ref name="manual">{{cite book | author=Sega staff |date=November 1986 | title=Black Belt ''Instruction Manual'' | url=https://archive.org/details/Black_Belt_1986_U/mode/1up | publisher=[[Sega|Sega of America]] | id=010086050547 | pages=2–10}}</ref><ref name="hcg101">{{cite web | author=Kulata, Kurt | date=December 18, 2007 | title=''Black Belt'' | url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/black-belt/amp/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230331124758/http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/black-belt/amp/ | archive-date=March 31, 2023 | website=[[Hardcore Gaming 101]] | accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref><ref name="computerentertainer"/> The player's [[health (game terminology)|health]] meter, remaining time, and [[Score (game)#Video games|score]] are displayed along the top of the screen. The score is increased by landing hits and defeating enemies. Should all the player's health or time deplete, one [[Life (video games)|life]] is lost. Additional health, time, and lives can be earned by increasing the score.<ref name="manual"/> [[Power-up]]s containing health, time, or temporary invincibility will also sometimes cross the top of the screen, requiring the player to perform a high jump to reach them.<ref name="hcg101"/><ref name="computerentertainer"/>

The player must confront and defeat a [[Boss (video games)|boss]] at the end of each stage to advance to the next chapter. These are one-on-one battles where the boss's health is displayed by a second meter under the player's own. The character [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] for these fights are  larger and more detailed.<ref name="hcg101"/><ref name="ignreview">{{cite web | author=Buchanan, Levi | date=January 11, 2008 | title=''Black Belt'' Review | url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/01/11/black-belt-review | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321225029/https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/01/11/black-belt-review | archive-date=March 21, 2016 | website=[[IGN]] | accessdate=January 7, 2024}}</ref> Each boss is susceptible to only one type of attack, demanding that the player exploit their opponent's weakness and use it to finish them off.<ref name="hcg101"/> The game contains an option that allows a [[Multiplayer video game|second player]] to alternate with the first.<ref name="manual"/>

==Development and release==
''Black Belt'' was developed and published by [[Sega]]. In Japan, the game was titled ''Hokuto no Ken'' and was an adaptation of the [[manga]] of the [[Fist of the North Star|same name]]. Mutsuhiro Fujii recalled that the company's design teams were working on about 20 titles simultaneously by the time the [[Master System#Mark III|Mark III]] went to market. Having just acquired the ''Hokuto no Ken'' license, his team created this game utilizing the console's improved one [[megabit]] cartridge technology.<ref>{{cite web | author=Sega staff | title=Vol. 05 ''Fantasy Zone'' (Sega Mark III) Masterpiece Interview | url=https://www.sega.jp/fb/album/05_fz/interview1.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231117115957/https://www.sega.jp/fb/album/05_fz/interview1.html | archive-date=November 17, 2023| publisher=[[Sega]] | language=ja | accessdate=December 12, 2023}}</ref>

While Fujii served an unknown role in its production, it was [[video game programmer|programmed]] by [[Yuji Naka]] prior to his involvement in the creation of ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''.<ref name="hcg101"/><ref name="ign2500">{{cite web | author=Gantayat, Anoop | title=''Sega Ages 2500: Hokuto no Ken'' Playtest | url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2004/07/13/sega-ages-2500-hokuto-no-ken-playtest | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230928194818/https://www.ign.com/articles/2004/07/13/sega-ages-2500-hokuto-no-ken-playtest | archive-date=September 28, 2023 | website=[[IGN]] | date=July 13, 2004 | accessdate=December 13, 2023}}</ref> Naka also created the bosses and enemies after having been given a rough outline of them from the planner. When he was unsure about their design he would read the relevant parts of the manga.<ref name="segamagazine">{{cite magazine | author=''Sega Magazine'' staff | date=January 1997 | title=ソニックチーム物語 | trans-title=Sonic Team Story | url=https://archive.org/details/sega-magazine-jp-issue-03-199701/page/n11/mode/2up | magazine=Sega Magazine | publisher=[[SoftBank Group|SoftBank]] | language=ja | issue=3 | pages=9–13}}</ref> Naka revealed that the team questioned if it was appropriate to integrate certain parts of the story into requirements for defeating bosses if some players were unfamiliar with the source material.<ref name="ign2500"/> For instance, one of the minibosses, [[List of Fist of the North Star characters#King|Heart]], can only be defeated by hitting his stomach.<ref name="creatorsnote">{{cite book | author=[[Yuji Naka|Naka Yuji]] | date=March 25, 2004 | title=Sega Ages 2500 Vol. 11 Hokuto no Ken | section=Creator's Note | url=https://i.ebayimg.com/images/g/UF0AAOSwPDhjxn21/s-l1600.jpg | publisher=[[Sega]] | language=ja | id=SLPM-62432 | access-date=December 14, 2023 | archive-date=December 10, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231210015009/https://i.ebayimg.com/images/g/UF0AAOSwPDhjxn21/s-l1600.jpg | url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref> Naka was heavily exposed to ''Hokuto no Ken'' through a friend before he accepted the Sega job, but professed he was not a fan.<ref name="segamagazine"/> He said it would have been interesting to see his career path had he done more fighting games.<ref name="ign2500"/><ref name="creatorsnote"/> The game's music and sound was composed by Katsuhiro Hayashi.<ref>{{cite web | author=Hayashi Katsuhiro | date=April 12, 2006 | title=林 克洋 プロフィ－ル  | trans-title=Katsuhiro Hayashi Profile | url=http://www.iris.dti.ne.jp/~haya-c/funkykh/profile.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230608062442/http://www.iris.dti.ne.jp/~haya-c/funkykh/profile.html | archive-date=June 8, 2023 | publisher=[[:ja:ドリーム・トレイン・インターネット|Dream Train Internet Co., Ltd.]] | language=ja | accessdate=February 3, 2024}}</ref>

''Hokuto no Ken'' was released in Japan on July 20, 1986.<ref>{{cite web | title=北斗の拳 | trans-title=''Fist of the North Star'' | url=https://vc.sega.jp/vc_ms_hokuto/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231101193405/https://vc.sega.jp/vc_ms_hokuto/ | archive-date=November 1, 2023 | publisher=[[Sega]] | accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref> The ''Black Belt'' localized version was first shown the month prior at the Summer [[Consumer Electronics Show]] alongside the Master System and its starting lineup of software titles for regions outside Japan.<ref>{{cite magazine | author=''Computer Entertainer'' staff | title=Plenty of Detail | date=July 1986 | url=https://archive.org/details/computer-entertainer-5-4 | magazine=[[Computer Entertainer]] | volume=5 | issue=4 | pages=1, 12 | issn=0890-2143}}</ref> Major alterations were made during localization to remove all ties to the ''Hokuto no Ken'' property. For ''Black Belt'', most of the character [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] and backgrounds were changed, some of the music is different, and more health restoratives were added.<ref name="hcg101"/> The gameplay mechanics remain the same and the lesser enemies still die by exploding into bits.<ref name="hcg101"/><ref name="wireframe">{{cite magazine | author=Dransfield, Ian | date=September 3, 2020 | title=Backwards Compatible: Made in Japan | url=https://archive.org/details/Wireframe42/page/105/mode/1up | magazine=Wireframe | publisher=[[Raspberry Pi Foundation|Raspberry Pi Press]] | issue=42 | page=105 | issn=2631-6730}}</ref> ''Black Belt'' was released in North America in November 1986 and in Europe in August 1987.<ref>{{cite magazine | title=Availability Update | author=''Computer Entertainer'' staff | date=December 1986 | url=https://archive.org/details/computer-entertainer-5-9/page/n13/mode/1up | magazine=[[Computer Entertainer]] | volume=5 | issue=9 | page=14 | issn=0890-2143}}</ref><ref name="Schnittberichte">{{cite web | title=''Black Belt'' | url=https://www.schnittberichte.com/svds.php?Page=Titel&ID=18807 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230604110734/https://www.schnittberichte.com/svds.php?Page=Titel&ID=18807 | archive-date=June 4, 2023 | website=Schnittberichte.com | language=de | accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref> [[Ariolasoft]] held the distribution rights to the game in the United Kingdom, Germany, and Holland.<ref>{{cite magazine | author=Cook, John | date=October 23–29, 1986 | title=Consolation for the games player | url=https://archive.org/details/NH2021_Popular_Computing_Weekly_Issue861023.pdf/page/n13/mode/2up | magazine=[[Popular Computing Weekly]] | publisher=[[Sunshine Publications]] | volume=5 | number=43 | pages=14–5 | issn=0265-0509}}</ref> However, due to violence, the game was [[List of banned video games by country|banned]] from sale to those under age 18 in Germany per the [[Protection of Young Persons Act (Germany)|Protection of Young Persons Act]] from 1987 to 2012.<ref name="Schnittberichte"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.master-system.info/indiziert.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816031431/http://www.master-system.info/indiziert.htm | archive-date=August 16, 2022 | title=Indizierte Spiele | trans-title=Indexed games | language=de | website=Master-System.info | accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref> [[Tectoy]] published the game in Brazil.<ref>{{cite magazine | author=''Ação Games'' staff | date=December 1990 | title=Master System: Tectoy — Sega | url=https://archive.org/details/acao-games/A%20Semana%20em%20A%C3%A7%C3%A3o%20-%20Especial%20Games%20%231%20%28Dezembro%201990%29/page/n47/mode/1up | magazine=[[Ação Games]] | publisher=[[Editora Abril]] | issue=1 | page=48 | language=pt | issn=0104-1630}}</ref>

Sega developed a 1989 sequel for the [[Sega Genesis|Mega Drive]], which was released internationally as ''[[Last Battle (video game)|Last Battle]]'' and was once again stripped of the ''Hokuto no Ken'' license.<ref>{{cite web | author=Buchanan, Levi | date=January 11, 2008 | title=''Last Battle'' Review | url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/01/11/last-battle-review | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200919071510/https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/01/11/last-battle-review | archive-date=September 19, 2020 | website=[[IGN]] | accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref> An enhanced [[video game remake|remake]] of ''Hokuto no Ken'' featuring [[3D computer graphics|3D polygonal graphics]] was released for the [[PlayStation 2]] in Japan on March 25, 2004 as the 11th entry in Sega's ''[[Sega Ages#Sega Ages 2500 (PlayStation 2)|Sega Ages 2500]]'' line, with the original version added as a bonus.<ref name="segaages">{{cite web | title=北斗の拳 | trans-title=''Fist of the North Star'' | url=http://sega.jp/ps2/ages11/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917134717/http://sega.jp/ps2/ages11/ | archive-date=September 17, 2015 | publisher=[[Sega]] | language=ja | accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref> Its inclusion was specifically requested by Naka.<ref name="creatorsnote"/> The Mark III version was digitally re-released in Japan for the [[Wii]] via the [[Virtual Console]] service on February 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite web | author=Nakano Shinji | date=January 25, 2008 | title=セガ、Wiiの「バーチャルコンソール」「マスターシステム」関連ソフトを配信。第1弾は「北斗の拳」| trans-title=Sega distributes Wii's Virtual Console and Master System related software. The first one is ''Fist of the North Star'' |  url=https://game.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/20080125/sega.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231021163906/https://game.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/20080125/sega.htm | archive-date=October 21, 2023 | website=[[:ja:Impress Watch|Impress Watch]] | language=ja | accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref> Naka was consulted about a [[software bug]] found in this emulation's [[ROM image]] and promptly fixed it just by looking at its [[computer code|code]].<ref>{{cite magazine | author=''Nintendo Power'' staff | date=June 2009 | title=Power Profiles: Yuji Naka | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230430010154/https://info.sonicretro.org/images/b/b6/NintendoPower_May2009_Page82.jpg | page=80 | issue=242 | magazine=[[Nintendo Power]] | publisher=[[Future US]] | issn=1041-9551}}</ref> The original game can also be unlocked in the 2018 [[PlayStation 4]] title ''[[Fist of the North Star: Lost Paradise]]''.<ref>{{cite web | author=Hetfield, Malindy | date=October 4, 2018 | title=''Fist of the North Star: Lost Paradise'' review - a lesser ''Yakuza'' | url=https://www.eurogamer.net/fist-of-the-north-star-lost-paradise-review-a-lesser-yakuza | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705011119/https://www.eurogamer.net/fist-of-the-north-star-lost-paradise-review-a-lesser-yakuza | archive-date=July 5, 2022 | publisher=[[Gamer Network]] | website=[[Eurogamer]] | accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref> The western release of ''Lost Paradise'' retains the original Japanese rendition of ''Hokuto no Ken'' rather than its ''Black Belt'' counterpart.<ref>{{cite web | author=Sánchez, Edgar | date=February 26, 2018 | title=Impresiones de ''Hokuto Ga Gotoku'' para PlayStation 4 | trans-title=Impressions of ''Hokuto Ga Gotoku'' for PlayStation 4 | url=https://vandal.elespanol.com/avances-amp/ps4/hokuto-ga-gotoku/51618/1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301044731/https://vandal.elespanol.com/avances-amp/ps4/hokuto-ga-gotoku/51618/1 | archive-date=March 1, 2018 | publisher=[[El Español]] | website=Vandal | language=es | accessdate=December 24, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Martinez, David | date=October 1, 2018 | title=Análisis de ''Fist of the North Star Lost Paradise'' para PS4 | trans-title=Analysis of ''Fist of the North Star Lost Paradise'' for PS4 | url=https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/reviews/analisis-fist-north-star-lost-paradise-ps4-308359 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231230132602/https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/reviews/analisis-fist-north-star-lost-paradise-ps4-308359 | archive-date=December 30, 2023 | publisher=Hobby Press | website=[[HobbyConsolas]] | language=es | accessdate=December 30, 2023}}</ref> Music tracks from both the Mark III and Master System versions were included on the ''Sega SG-1000 30th Anniversary Collection'' album released by Wave Master in Japan on July 31, 2013.<ref>{{cite web | title=セガ SG-1000 30th アニバーサリーコレクション | trans-title=''Sega SG-1000 30th Anniversary Collection'' | url=https://www.wave-master.com/ent/details/wm/wm0703/index.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220817005642/https://www.wave-master.com/ent/details/wm/wm0703/index.html | archive-date=August 17, 2022 | publisher=[[Sega Sammy Holdings|Wave Master Inc.]] | language=ja | accessdate=January 6, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Totsuka Kiichi | date=July 31, 2013 | title=往年のセガファン感涙必至！　名曲尽くしの『セガ SG-1000 30th アニバーサリーコレクション』が実現に至るまで | trans-title=Old Sega fans will definitely be moved to tears! How the ''Sega SG-1000 30th Anniversary Collection'' full of famous songs came to fruition | url=https://www.famitsu.com/news/amp/201307/31037434.php | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200521080320/https://www.famitsu.com/news/amp/201307/31037434.php | archive-date=May 21, 2020 | publisher=[[Kadokawa Future Publishing|Kadokawa Game Linkage]] | website=[[Famitsu]] | language=ja | accessdate=January 6, 2024}}</ref>

