Critical reception for ''Black Belt'' has been mixed. Print and online media outlets disagreed on the quality of its visuals and gameplay while commonly comparing it to [[Irem]]'s ''[[Kung-Fu Master (video game)|Kung-Fu Master]]''. A duplicate review from ''[[Mean Machines|Mean Machines Sega]]'' and ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' in their "Complete Guide to Consoles" highly recommended ''Black Belt'' for being "tough and challenging" and one of Sega's better beat 'em ups.<ref name="cvg2"/> ''[[Hardcore Gaming 101]]'' founder Kurt Kulata noted it as "little more than a rip-off" of ''Kung-Fu Master''" but with better controls and more varied level design. Combined with "fantastic visuals" such as its "extremely impressive" use of [[parallax scrolling]] for backgrounds, he declared ''Black Belt'' one of the Master System's finest games in the console's early line-up.<ref name="hcg101"/> Kulata, Levi Buchanan of ''[[IGN]]'', and the French magazine ''[[:fr:Gen4|Génération 4]]'' all described the one-on-one [[fighting video game|fighting]] boss battles as its highlight. Both Kukata and Buchanan noted this preceded the same feature popularized in [[Capcom]]'s ''[[Street Fighter (video game)|Street Fighter]]''.<ref name="hcg101"/><ref name="ignreview"/> ''[[Computer Entertainer]]'' editor Celeste Dolan positively likened the protagonist's [[superhuman]] abilities to those seen in some [[martial arts film]]s, concluding that the game contained "good, frenzied action with plenty of challenge".<ref name="computerentertainer">{{cite magazine | title=Critically Speaking...Sega Compatible | author=Dolan, Celeste | date=December 1986 | url=https://archive.org/details/computer-entertainer-5-9/page/12/mode/1up | magazine=[[Computer Entertainer]] | volume=5 | issue=9 | page=12 | issn=0890-2143}}</ref> ''[[1Up Network|Retronauts]]'' was recommendatory of the original Japanese version owing to its graphics, fast-paced action, and faithfulness to its source material. The writers declared, "It's definitely a game that shows its age but compared to the licensed [[shovelware]] of the era (not least of all, the very similar but far worse ''[[Fist of the North Star (NES video game)|Hokuto no Ken]]'' game released for [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Famicom]] just weeks after this one) it's not hard to see why this game is still fondly remembered as both a great ''Hokuto no Ken'' game and a great Mark III title."<ref name="retronauts">{{cite web | author=Mackey, Bob and Parrish, Jeremy | date=June 12, 2018 | title=The seven stars of the ''Fist of the North Star'' catalogue | url=https://retronauts.com/article/702/the-seven-stars-of-the-fist-of-the-north-star-catalogue-wip?amphtml=1 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614012225/https://retronauts.com/article/702/the-seven-stars-of-the-fist-of-the-north-star-catalogue-wip | archive-date=June 14, 2018 | website=[[1Up Network|Retronauts.com]] | accessdate=December 23, 2023}}</ref>

''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' labeled ''Black Belt'' a "straight ahead imitator" of ''Kung-Fu Master'' and the most traditional among Sega's Master System martial arts games. The magazine commended the game's inclusion of a basic plot and its instruction booklet's differentiation of oriental combat styles but mocked its translation.<ref>{{cite magazine | title=Video Gaming World | magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] | issue=52 | date=October 1988 | url=https://archive.org/details/Computer_Gaming_World_Issue_52/page/n47/mode/2up | last1=Worley | first1=Joyce | last2=Kunkel | first2=Bill | last3=Katz | first3=Arnie | pages=48–9 | publisher=Golden Empire Publications, Inc. | issn=0744-6667}}</ref> Buchanan criticized the potential for the player to die during boss fights and then have to start the entire game over.<ref name="ignreview"/> Several critics believed the gameplay of fighting through waves of enemies to be monotonous. ''[[Sega Power]]'' contributor Steve Jarrett found the end-stage bosses to be decent but the stages leading up to them to be "painfully repetitive".<ref name="segapower"/> Another duplicate assessment in ''[[Paragon Publishing#Console XS|Console XS]]'' and ''[[Sega Pro]]'' likewise described the objectives as "unexciting and repetitive" as well as "criminally easy" while additionally calling the graphics "incredibly poor".<ref name="consolexs"/><ref name="segapro2"/> Dolan appreciated the game's presentation overall but was dismayed by the lack of detail in the character sprites and an excessive amount of [[flicker (screen)|flicker]].<ref name="computerentertainer"/> Websites including ''IGN'', ''[[Comic Book Resources|CBR]]'', ''[[Screen Rant]]'', ''[[WatchMojo]]'', and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' all mentioned the localized [[Video game packaging#Box art|box art]] of ''Black Belt'' as being among the worst of generally bad Master System game covers.<ref name="ignreview"/><ref>{{cite web | author=Lambrechts, Stephen | date=November 8, 2010 | title=Judging a Game by its Cover | url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2010/11/08/judging-a-game-by-its-cover | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221128035759/https://www.ign.com/articles/2010/11/08/judging-a-game-by-its-cover | archive-date=November 28, 2022 | website=[[IGN]] | accessdate=December 24, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Arellano, Patrick | date=July 30, 2022 | title=10 Cringeworthy Video Game Covers | url=https://www.cbr.com/most-cringeworthy-video-game-covers/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221122153623/https://www.cbr.com/most-cringeworthy-video-game-covers/ | archive-date=November 22, 2022 | website=[[Comic Book Resources|CBR]] | publisher=Valnet Inc. | accessdate=December 26, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Lynch, Ryan | date=August 4, 2016 | title=15 Wonderfully Bad Retro Video Game Box Covers | url=https://screenrant.com/wonderfully-bad-retro-video-game-box-art/#my-hero-black-belt-master-system-1986 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811210138/https://screenrant.com/wonderfully-bad-retro-video-game-box-art/ | archive-date=August 11, 2016 | publisher=Valnet, Inc. | website=[[Screen Rant]] | accessdate=December 26, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Steiner, Chris | date=June 22, 2016 | title=Top 10 Worst Video Game Box Arts | url=https://www.watchmojo.com/amp/articles/top-10-worst-video-game-box-arts | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231226152712/https://www.watchmojo.com/amp/articles/top-10-worst-video-game-box-arts | archive-date=December 26, 2023 | website=[[WatchMojo]] | accessdate=December 26, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Graham, Bryan Armen | date=April 25, 2013 | title=17 Examples of Sports Video Game Cover Art That Make Other Art Embarrassed to Be Art | url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2013/04/25/17-examples-of-sports-video-game-cover-art-that-makes-other-art-embarrassed-to-be-art | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112025636/https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2013/04/25/17-examples-of-sports-video-game-cover-art-that-makes-other-art-embarrassed-to-be-art | archive-date=November 12, 2020 | website=[[Sports Illustrated]] | accessdate=December 26, 2023}}</ref>

